events.description: Battle of Rovine: The Wallachians defeat an invading Ottoman army.
events.html: • 1395 – Battle of Rovine: The Wallachians defeat an invading Ottoman army.[1]

events.description: Edward Stafford, 3rd Duke of Buckingham, is executed for treason.
events.html: • 1521 – Edward Stafford, 3rd Duke of Buckingham, is executed for treason.[2]

events.description: Pánfilo de Narváez departs Spain to explore Florida with 600 men
events.html: • 1527 – Pánfilo de Narváez departs Spain to explore Florida with 600 men – by 1536 only four survive.[3]

events.description: George Boleyn, 2nd Viscount Rochford and four other men are executed for treason.
events.html: • 1536 – George Boleyn, 2nd Viscount Rochford and four other men are executed for treason.

events.description: Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn's marriage is annulled.
events.html: • 1536 – Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn's marriage is annulled.

events.description: Anne of Denmark is crowned Queen of Scotland.
events.html: • 1590 – Anne of Denmark is crowned Queen of Scotland.

events.description: Paul de Chomedey, Sieur de Maisonneuve founds the Ville Marie de Montréal.
events.html: • 1642 – Paul de Chomedey, Sieur de Maisonneuve founds the Ville Marie de Montréal.

entities.name: Paul de Chomedey, Sieur de Maisonneuve

events.description: An allied French and Swedish army defeats Imperial and Bavarian forces in the Battle of Zusmarshausen.
events.html: • 1648 – An allied French and Swedish army defeats Imperial and Bavarian forces in the Battle of Zusmarshausen.[4]

events.description: Louis Jolliet and Jacques Marquette begin exploring the Mississippi River.
events.html: • 1673 – Louis Jolliet and Jacques Marquette begin exploring the Mississippi River.

events.description: Seven Years' War formally begins when Great Britain declares war on France
events.html: • 1756 – Seven Years' War formally begins when Great Britain declares war on France

events.description: French forces besieging Quebec retreat after the Royal Navy arrives to relieve the British garrison.
events.html: • 1760 – French forces besieging Quebec retreat after the Royal Navy arrives to relieve the British garrison.[5]

events.description: The New York Stock Exchange is formed under the Buttonwood Agreement.
events.html: • 1792 – The New York Stock Exchange is formed under the Buttonwood Agreement.

events.description: Muhammad Ali becomes Wāli of Egypt.
events.html: • 1805 – Muhammad Ali becomes Wāli of Egypt.

events.description: Emperor Napoleon I orders the annexation of the Papal States to the French Empire.
events.html: • 1809 – Emperor Napoleon I orders the annexation of the Papal States to the French Empire.[6]

events.description: Occupation of Monaco changes from French to Austrian.
events.html: • 1814 – Occupation of Monaco changes from French to Austrian.

events.description: The Constitution of Norway is signed and Crown Prince Christian Frederick of Denmark is elected King of Norway by the Norwegian Constituent Assembly.
events.html: • 1814 – The Constitution of Norway is signed and Crown Prince Christian Frederick of Denmark is elected King of Norway by the Norwegian Constituent Assembly.

events.description: Members of the Melbourne Football Club codified the first rules of Australian rules football.
events.html: • 1859 – Members of the Melbourne Football Club codified the first rules of Australian rules football.

events.description: Rosalía de Castro publishes Cantares Gallegos, the first book in the Galician language.
events.html: • 1863 – Rosalía de Castro publishes Cantares Gallegos, the first book in the Galician language.

events.description: American Civil War: During the Vicksburg campaign, Union forces under John A. McClernand defeat a Confederate rearguard and capture around 1,700 men at the Battle of Big Black River Bridge.
events.html: • 1863 – American Civil War: During the Vicksburg campaign, Union forces under John A. McClernand defeat a Confederate rearguard and capture around 1,700 men at the Battle of Big Black River Bridge.[7]

entities.name: Battle of Big Black River Bridge

events.description: The International Telegraph Union (later the International Telecommunication Union) is established in Paris.
events.html: • 1865 – The International Telegraph Union (later the International Telecommunication Union) is established in Paris.

events.description: Aristides wins the first Kentucky Derby with the jockey Oliver Lewis (2:37.75).
events.html: • 1875 – Aristides wins the first Kentucky Derby with the jockey Oliver Lewis (2:37.75).

events.description: The children's novel The Wonderful Wizard of Oz, by L. Frank Baum, is first published in the United States. The first copy is given to the author's sister.
events.html: • 1900 – The children's novel The Wonderful Wizard of Oz, by L. Frank Baum, is first published in the United States. The first copy is given to the author's sister.[8]

events.description: Greek archaeologist Valerios Stais discovers the Antikythera mechanism, an ancient mechanical analog computer.
events.html: • 1902 – Greek archaeologist Valerios Stais discovers the Antikythera mechanism, an ancient mechanical analog computer.

events.description: The Protocol of Corfu is signed, recognising full autonomy to Northern Epirus under nominal Albanian sovereignty.
events.html: • 1914 – The Protocol of Corfu is signed, recognising full autonomy to Northern Epirus under nominal Albanian sovereignty.

events.description: The last British Liberal Party government (led by H. H. Asquith) falls.
events.html: • 1915 – The last British Liberal Party government (led by H. H. Asquith) falls.

events.description: Vidkun Quisling and Johan Bernhard Hjort form Nasjonal Samling — the national-socialist party of Norway.
events.html: • 1933 – Vidkun Quisling and Johan Bernhard Hjort form Nasjonal Samling — the national-socialist party of Norway.

events.description: Spanish Civil War: The Largo Caballero government resigns in the wake of the Barcelona May Days, leading Juan Negrín to form a government, without the anarcho-syndicalist CNT, in its stead.
events.html: • 1937 – Spanish Civil War: The Largo Caballero government resigns in the wake of the Barcelona May Days, leading Juan Negrín to form a government, without the anarcho-syndicalist CNT, in its stead.[9]

events.description: The Columbia Lions and the Princeton Tigers play in the United States' first televised sporting event, a collegiate baseball game in New York City.
events.html: • 1939 – The Columbia Lions and the Princeton Tigers play in the United States' first televised sporting event, a collegiate baseball game in New York City.

events.description: World War II: Germany occupies Brussels, Belgium.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Germany occupies Brussels, Belgium.

events.description: World War II: Dambuster Raids commence by No. 617 Squadron RAF.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: Dambuster Raids commence by No. 617 Squadron RAF.

events.description: Delta Air Lines Flight 318 crashes near Marshall, Texas, killing 19.
events.html: • 1953 – Delta Air Lines Flight 318 crashes near Marshall, Texas, killing 19.[10]

events.description: The United States Supreme Court hands down a unanimous decision in Brown v. Board of Education of Topeka, Kansas, outlawing racial segregation in public schools.
events.html: • 1954 – The United States Supreme Court hands down a unanimous decision in Brown v. Board of Education of Topeka, Kansas, outlawing racial segregation in public schools.

events.description: Six-Day War: President Gamal Abdel Nasser of Egypt demands dismantling of the peace-keeping UN Emergency Force in Egypt.
events.html: • 1967 – Six-Day War: President Gamal Abdel Nasser of Egypt demands dismantling of the peace-keeping UN Emergency Force in Egypt.

events.description: Venera program: Soviet Venera 6 begins its descent into the atmosphere of Venus, sending back atmospheric data before being crushed by pressure.
events.html: • 1969 – Venera program: Soviet Venera 6 begins its descent into the atmosphere of Venus, sending back atmospheric data before being crushed by pressure.

events.description: Watergate scandal: Televised hearings begin in the United States Senate.
events.html: • 1973 – Watergate scandal: Televised hearings begin in the United States Senate.

events.description: The Troubles: Thirty-three civilians are killed and 300 injured when the Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF) detonates four car bombs in Dublin and Monaghan, Republic of Ireland.
events.html: • 1974 – The Troubles: Thirty-three civilians are killed and 300 injured when the Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF) detonates four car bombs in Dublin and Monaghan, Republic of Ireland.

events.description: Police in Los Angeles raid the Symbionese Liberation Army's headquarters, killing six members, including Camilla Hall.
events.html: • 1974 – Police in Los Angeles raid the Symbionese Liberation Army's headquarters, killing six members, including Camilla Hall.

events.description: Nolan Bushnell opened the first Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre (later renamed Chuck E. Cheese) in San Jose, California.
events.html: • 1977 – Nolan Bushnell opened the first Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre (later renamed Chuck E. Cheese) in San Jose, California.

events.description: General Chun Doo-hwan of South Korea seizes control of the government and declares martial law in order to suppress student demonstrations.
events.html: • 1980 – General Chun Doo-hwan of South Korea seizes control of the government and declares martial law in order to suppress student demonstrations.

events.description: On the eve of presidential elections, Maoist guerrilla group Shining Path attacks a polling location in Chuschi (a town in Ayacucho), starting the Internal conflict in Peru.
events.html: • 1980 – On the eve of presidential elections, Maoist guerrilla group Shining Path attacks a polling location in Chuschi (a town in Ayacucho), starting the Internal conflict in Peru.

events.description: The U.S. Department of Energy declassifies documents showing world's largest mercury pollution event in Oak Ridge, Tennessee (ultimately found to be 4.2 million pounds [1.9 kt]), in response to the Appalachian Observer's Freedom of Information Act request.
events.html: • 1983 – The U.S. Department of Energy declassifies documents showing world's largest mercury pollution event in Oak Ridge, Tennessee (ultimately found to be 4.2 million pounds [1.9 kt]), in response to the Appalachian Observer's Freedom of Information Act request.

events.description: Lebanon, Israel, and the United States sign an agreement on Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
events.html: • 1983 – Lebanon, Israel, and the United States sign an agreement on Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.

events.description: Prince Charles calls a proposed addition to the National Gallery, London, a "monstrous carbuncle on the face of a much-loved and elegant friend", sparking controversies on the proper role of the Royal Family and the course of modern architecture.
events.html: • 1984 – Prince Charles calls a proposed addition to the National Gallery, London, a "monstrous carbuncle on the face of a much-loved and elegant friend", sparking controversies on the proper role of the Royal Family and the course of modern architecture.

entities.name: Charles III of the United Kingdom

events.description: Iran–Iraq War: An Iraqi Dassault Mirage F1 fighter jet fires two missiles into the U.S. Navy warship USS Stark, killing 37 and injuring 21 of her crew.
events.html: • 1987 – Iran–Iraq War: An Iraqi Dassault Mirage F1 fighter jet fires two missiles into the U.S. Navy warship USS Stark, killing 37 and injuring 21 of her crew.

events.description: The General Assembly of the World Health Organization (WHO) eliminates homosexuality from the list of psychiatric diseases.
events.html: • 1990 – The General Assembly of the World Health Organization (WHO) eliminates homosexuality from the list of psychiatric diseases.

events.description: Three days of popular protests against the government of Prime Minister of Thailand Suchinda Kraprayoon begin in Bangkok, leading to a military crackdown that results in 52 officially confirmed deaths, hundreds of injuries, many disappearances, and more than 3,500 arrests.
events.html: • 1992 – Three days of popular protests against the government of Prime Minister of Thailand Suchinda Kraprayoon begin in Bangkok, leading to a military crackdown that results in 52 officially confirmed deaths, hundreds of injuries, many disappearances, and more than 3,500 arrests.

events.description: Malawi holds its first multi-party elections.
events.html: • 1994 – Malawi holds its first multi-party elections.

events.description: Shawn Nelson steals an M60 tank from the California Army National Guard Armory in San Diego and proceeds to go on a rampage.
events.html: • 1995 – Shawn Nelson steals an M60 tank from the California Army National Guard Armory in San Diego and proceeds to go on a rampage.

events.description: Troops of Laurent-Désiré Kabila march into Kinshasa. Zaire is officially renamed Democratic Republic of the Congo.
events.html: • 1997 – Troops of Laurent-Désiré Kabila march into Kinshasa. Zaire is officially renamed Democratic Republic of the Congo.

events.description: Arsenal and Galatasaray fans clash in the 2000 UEFA Cup Final riots in Copenhagen
events.html: • 2000 – Arsenal and Galatasaray fans clash in the 2000 UEFA Cup Final riots in Copenhagen

events.html: • 2004 – The first legal same-sex marriages in the U.S. are performed in the state of Massachusetts.

events.description: The aircraft carrier USS Oriskany is sunk in the Gulf of Mexico as an artificial reef.
events.html: • 2006 – The aircraft carrier USS Oriskany is sunk in the Gulf of Mexico as an artificial reef.

events.description: Trains from North and South Korea cross the 38th Parallel in a test-run agreed by both governments. This is the first time that trains have crossed the Demilitarized Zone since 1953.
